        "content": "import pytest\nimport sqlite3\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\nfrom models import Job\nfrom store import Store\n\n\ndef make_job(external_id=\"1\", **kw):\n    base = dict(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=external_id,\n                title=\"Engineer\", url=\"https://x/1\")\n    base.update(kw)\n    return Job(**base)\n\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef store(tmp_path):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"test.db\") as s:\n        yield s\n\n\nclass TestDiff:\n    def test_first_seen_job_is_new(self, store):\n        new, changed = store.diff([make_job()])\n        assert len(new) == 1 and changed == []\n\n    def test_unchanged_job_on_second_run_is_neither(self, store):\n        store.diff([make_job()])\n        new, changed = store.diff([make_job()])\n        assert new == [] and changed == []\n\n    def test_changed_title_marks_as_changed(self, store):\n        store.diff([make_job(title=\"Engineer I\")])\n        new, changed = store.diff([make_job(title=\"Engineer II\")])\n        assert new == [] and len(changed) == 1\n\n    def test_different_company_same_source_is_separate_row(self, store):\n        store.diff([make_job()])\n        new, _ = store.diff([make_job(source=\"greenhouse\")], )\n        # same source/company/external_id => same key, no duplicate\n        assert store.count() == 1\n\n    def test_diff_persists_across_reopen(self, tmp_path):\n        path = tmp_path / \"persist.db\"\n        with Store(path) as s:\n            s.diff([make_job()])\n        with Store(path) as s2:\n            assert s2.count() == 1\n\n\nclass TestMigration:\n    def test_migrates_db_missing_salary_range_column(self, tmp_path):\n        path = tmp_path / \"legacy.db\"\n        conn = sqlite3.connect(str(path))\n        conn.executescript(\"\"\"\n            CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT, company TEXT,\n                external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT,\n                department TEXT, employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT,\n                content_hash TEXT, first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT);\n        \"\"\")\n        conn.commit()\n        conn.close()\n        with Store(path) as s:  # must not raise\n            cols = {r[\"name\"] for r in s.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n            assert \"salary_range\" in cols\n\n\nclass TestMeta:\n    def test_set_meta_upserts_not_duplicates(self, store):\n        store.set_meta(\"last_scan\", \"2026-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\")\n        store.set_meta(\"last_scan\", \"2026-01-02T00:00:00+00:00\")\n        assert store.get_meta(\"last_scan\") == \"2026-01-02T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\n    def test_get_meta_missing_key_returns_none(self, store):\n        assert store.get_meta(\"nope\") is None\n\n\nclass TestAddedSince:\n    def test_returns_only_rows_strictly_after_ts(self, store):\n        store.diff([make_job(external_id=\"1\")])\n        ts = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n        store.diff([make_job(external_id=\"2\")])\n        rows = store.added_since(ts)\n        assert {r[\"external_id\"] for r in rows} == {\"2\"} or rows == []\n        # NOTE: same-second writes are indistinguishable — worth flagging (see gaps below)\n```\n\n> **Gap worth flagging to the team:** `added_since` uses second-resolution ISO timestamps for a strict `>` comparison. Two `diff()` calls within the same wall-clock second (realistic in tests, and possible in a fast CI run) are indistinguishable, so a \"new since last scan\" boundary test needs `freezegun` or a manual timestamp injection rather than relying on real clock ticks.\n\n---\n\n",
        "level": 1
      },
      {
        "title": "4. `pipeline.py` — no integration test exists for the orchestration path at all",
        "content": "\n**Untested:** `load_config` defaults, `run()` end-to-end, `dry_run` branch, `run_sync`.\n\n**Edge cases:**\n- `load_config` default-filling (`sources`, `filters`, `db`, `concurrency`) when the YAML omits them.\n- `dry_run=True` must not touch the `Store` (no dedup writes) and must return `{\"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}` even when jobs matched.\n- Non-dry-run path must call `dispatch(new, changed)` — a regression here means silent notification loss.\n\n```python\n",
